<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911017-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>911017-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Nonprofit School Entity   Opens Grant Competition</HL><DATE>10/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><NS>EDUCATION ISSUES (EDU)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The nonprofit school corporation inspired byPresident Bush opened a national competition for $200 millionin grants to design a &quot;new generation&quot; of American schools.   The New American Schools Development Corp., based inArlington, Va., has encouraged businesses, organizations,educators and others to form teams to compete for the grantmoney. Yesterday, it invited teams to submit proposals forcontracts.</LP><TEXT>   The goal is to design a school or educational system thatcan be adopted in communities across the country.   The corporation was set up this spring by a group ofprominent chief executives at the request of President Bush.So far, it has raised $36 million in private contributionsand hopes to collect $200 million over the next five yearsfor a three-phase bidding process. It plans to award thefirst round of contracts to about 30 design teams in April.</TEXT></DOC>